## 6. Plugin #4: Entity Framework Plugin (`entity-framework`)

### 6.1 What It Extracts

Entity-to-table mappings, column definitions, relationships (FK, navigation properties), and the full database schema as inferred by EF Core.

### 6.2 Three Configuration Paths

#### Path A: Conventions (Implicit)

EF Core follows naming conventions — these require **inference** rather than explicit extraction:

```csharp
public class User
{
    public int Id { get; set; }          // Convention: "Id" or "{ClassName}Id" = PK
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int DepartmentId { get; set; } // Convention: "{NavProp}Id" = FK
    public Department Department { get; set; } // Navigation property → relationship
    public ICollection<Order> Orders { get; set; } // Collection nav → one-to-many
}

public class Department
{
    public int DepartmentId { get; set; } // Convention: "{ClassName}Id" = PK
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<User> Users { get; set; }
}
```

**Convention rules to implement:**
- Property named `Id` or `{ClassName}Id` → primary key
- Property named `{NavigationPropertyName}Id` or `{NavigationPropertyName}{PK}` → foreign key
- Reference navigation property (single entity type) → relationship to that entity
- Collection navigation property (`ICollection<T>`, `IEnumerable<T>`, `List<T>`, `IList<T>`) → one-to-many relationship from T
- Table name = class name (pluralized by EF Core, but we use the class name as-is for v1)

#### Path B: Data Annotations (Attributes)

```csharp
[Table("tbl_users")]
public class User
{
    [Key]
    public int UserId { get; set; }

    [Column("user_name")]
    [Required]
    [MaxLength(100)]
    public string Name { get; set; }

    [ForeignKey("Department")]
    public int DeptId { get; set; }

    [NotMapped]
    public string FullName => $"{FirstName} {LastName}";

    [InverseProperty("Author")]
    public ICollection<Post> Posts { get; set; }
}
```

**Attributes to handle:**
- `[Table("name")]` → explicit table name
- `[Column("name")]` → explicit column name
- `[Key]` → primary key
- `[ForeignKey("nav_property")]` → explicit FK reference
- `[Required]` → NOT NULL constraint
- `[MaxLength(n)]` → column length constraint
- `[NotMapped]` → skip this property entirely
- `[InverseProperty("name")]` → disambiguate bidirectional navigation
- `[Index]` / `[Index(IsUnique = true)]` → index definition

**Extraction:** Same tree-sitter attribute parsing as ASP.NET controllers. Match `attribute_list` on `property_declaration` nodes within entity classes.

#### Path C: Fluent API (in `OnModelCreating`)

```csharp
public class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<User> Users { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Department> Departments { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Order> Orders { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        // Table mapping
        modelBuilder.Entity<User>().ToTable("tbl_users");

        // Column mapping
        modelBuilder.Entity<User>().Property(u => u.Name)
            .HasColumnName("user_name")
            .HasMaxLength(100)
            .IsRequired();

        // One-to-many
        modelBuilder.Entity<User>()
            .HasOne(u => u.Department)
            .WithMany(d => d.Users)
            .HasForeignKey(u => u.DepartmentId);

        // One-to-one
        modelBuilder.Entity<User>()
            .HasOne(u => u.Profile)
            .WithOne(p => p.User)
            .HasForeignKey<UserProfile>(p => p.UserId);

        // Many-to-many (EF Core 5+ skip navigation)
        modelBuilder.Entity<Student>()
            .HasMany(s => s.Courses)
            .WithMany(c => c.Students)
            .UsingEntity(j => j.ToTable("StudentCourses"));

        // Many-to-many (explicit join entity)
        modelBuilder.Entity<StudentCourse>()
            .HasKey(sc => new { sc.StudentId, sc.CourseId });
        modelBuilder.Entity<StudentCourse>()
            .HasOne(sc => sc.Student)
            .WithMany(s => s.StudentCourses)
            .HasForeignKey(sc => sc.StudentId);
    }
}
```

**Also handle `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>` pattern:**

```csharp
public class UserConfiguration : IEntityTypeConfiguration<User>
{
    public void Configure(EntityTypeBuilder<User> builder)
    {
        builder.ToTable("tbl_users");
        builder.HasKey(u => u.Id);
        builder.HasOne(u => u.Department).WithMany(d => d.Users);
    }
}

// Registered in DbContext:
modelBuilder.ApplyConfigurationsFromAssembly(Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly());
```

**Fluent API extraction strategy:**

This is the most complex extraction path. The approach:

1. Find classes inheriting `DbContext` → extract `DbSet<T>` properties to discover entity types
2. Find `OnModelCreating` method → walk `invocation_expression` chains
3. For each `modelBuilder.Entity<T>()` call, identify the entity type from generic argument
4. Walk the chained method calls:
   - `.ToTable("name")` → explicit table name
   - `.HasOne(lambda)` → start of relationship, extract navigation property from lambda body
   - `.WithMany(lambda)` → one-to-many relationship type
   - `.WithOne(lambda)` → one-to-one relationship type
   - `.HasForeignKey(lambda)` → FK property extraction
   - `.HasMany(lambda).WithMany(lambda)` → many-to-many
   - `.UsingEntity(...)` → join table configuration
   - `.HasKey(lambda)` → composite or explicit key
   - `.Property(lambda).HasColumnName("name")` → column mapping

5. Also find classes implementing `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>` and parse their `Configure` method identically

**Lambda extraction challenge:** Lambda expressions like `u => u.Department` require resolving the member access to the property name. Tree-sitter parses these as `lambda_expression → member_access_expression` — we extract the rightmost identifier as the property/navigation name.

### 6.3 DbContext Discovery

```csharp
public class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<User> Users { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Order> Orders { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Product> Products { get; set; }
}
```

`DbSet<T>` properties register entity types. The generic type argument tells us which classes are EF entities. Classes not registered via `DbSet` but referenced via navigation properties are also entities (discovered transitively).

### 6.4 Migration Files

Migration files (`Migrations/*.cs`) contain schema operations:

```csharp
migrationBuilder.CreateTable(
    name: "Users",
    columns: table => new
    {
        Id = table.Column<int>(nullable: false).Annotation("..."),
        Name = table.Column<string>(maxLength: 100, nullable: false),
        DepartmentId = table.Column<int>(nullable: false)
    },
    constraints: table =>
    {
        table.PrimaryKey("PK_Users", x => x.Id);
        table.ForeignKey("FK_Users_Departments_DepartmentId",
            x => x.DepartmentId, "Departments", "Id",
            onDelete: ReferentialAction.Cascade);
    });
```

**Strategy:** Parse `CreateTable`, `AddColumn`, `AddForeignKey`, `CreateIndex` calls. This provides a **ground truth** for the database schema that can validate/supplement the entity model analysis.

### 6.5 Output

- **Nodes:**
  - `(:Table {name: "tbl_users", framework: "entity-framework"})` — FQN: `table:tbl_users`
  - `(:Column {name: "user_name", column_type: "string", is_primary_key: false, is_nullable: false})` — FQN: `table:tbl_users.user_name`
- **Edges:**
  - `(:Class)-[:MAPS_TO {orm: "entity-framework"}]->(:Table)`
  - `(:Table)-[:HAS_COLUMN]->(:Column)`
  - `(:Column)-[:REFERENCES {relationship: "many-to-one|one-to-one"}]->(:Column)` (FK → PK)
- **Layer assignments:** Entity classes → Data Access layer

### 6.6 Estimated Accuracy

| Configuration Path | Accuracy | Notes |
|-------------------|----------|-------|
| Data Annotations | ~90% | Attribute parsing is straightforward |
| Fluent API (simple) | ~80% | `HasOne/WithMany/HasForeignKey` chains |
| Fluent API (complex) | ~70-75% | Multi-step chaining, `UsingEntity`, composite keys |
| Convention-based | ~70% | Requires inference, nullable FK heuristics |
| Migration files | ~90% | Explicit schema operations |
| `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>` | ~75% | Need to trace `ApplyConfigurationsFromAssembly` |
| DbContext discovery | ~95% | `DbSet<T>` extraction is simple |

