## 9. Cross-Cutting Concerns

### 9.1 Layer Classification Rules

All .NET plugins share these layer rules:

| Pattern | Layer | Rule |
|---------|-------|------|
| Class inherits `ControllerBase` or `Controller` | Presentation | Name or attribute match |
| Class has `[ApiController]` attribute | Presentation | Attribute match |
| Class inherits `Hub` or `Hub<T>` | Presentation | SignalR hub |
| Class inherits `*.GreeterBase` (gRPC) | Presentation | gRPC service |
| Class name ends with `Service` | Business Logic | Convention |
| Class name ends with `Repository` | Data Access | Convention |
| Class inherits `DbContext` | Data Access | EF Core context |
| Entity class (has `DbSet<T>` registration) | Data Access | EF entity |
| Class implements `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>` | Data Access | EF configuration |
| Custom middleware class | Cross-Cutting | Has `Invoke/InvokeAsync` method |

### 9.2 Detection Strategy (Shared)

All plugins use `.csproj` package reference parsing + tree-sitter code scanning:

| Plugin | Detection Signal | Confidence |
|--------|-----------------|------------|
| `aspnet-di` | `Microsoft.AspNetCore` in `.csproj` | HIGH |
| `aspnet-web` | `[ApiController]` attribute OR `MapGet`/`MapPost` calls | HIGH |
| `aspnet-middleware` | `Use*()` calls on `WebApplication` variable | HIGH |
| `entity-framework` | `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` in `.csproj` OR `DbContext` subclass | HIGH |
| `aspnet-signalr` | `Microsoft.AspNetCore.SignalR` in `.csproj` OR `Hub` subclass | HIGH |
| `aspnet-grpc` | `Grpc.AspNetCore` in `.csproj` OR `MapGrpcService` call | HIGH |

### 9.3 Dependency Chain

```
aspnet-di (foundation — no dependencies)
  ├── aspnet-web (needs DI map for controller constructor injection)
  ├── aspnet-middleware (needs DI map for custom middleware injection)
  ├── entity-framework (needs DI map for DbContext injection)
  ├── aspnet-signalr (needs DI map for hub constructor injection)
  └── aspnet-grpc (needs DI map for service constructor injection)
```

All five downstream plugins depend on `aspnet-di`. They are independent of each other and can run in parallel.

### 9.4 Architecture View Contribution

The .NET plugins should contribute to the Architecture View with these Technology nodes:

- `ASP.NET Core` (Web framework)
- `Entity Framework Core` (ORM)
- `SignalR` (Real-time)
- `gRPC` (RPC)
- Plus any middleware technologies detected (Authentication, CORS, Rate Limiting, etc.)

This follows the same `create_technology_nodes()` enrichment pattern designed for the Architecture View fix.

### 9.5 Node Convention Mapping

C# nodes from tree-sitter (stored in `node.properties["annotations"]`) follow these conventions:

- **Attributes:** Stored as `["[ApiController]", "[Route(\"api/[controller]\")]", "[HttpGet(\"{id}\")]"]` — full attribute text including brackets and arguments
- **Base types:** Available via `INHERITS` edges: `(:Class)-[:INHERITS]->(:Class {fqn: "ControllerBase"})`
- **Properties:** `(:Field {name: "Users", properties: {type: "DbSet<User>"}})` — generic types preserved in type string
- **Parameters:** `properties["params"]` on methods = `[{"name": "id", "type": "int"}, {"name": "dto", "type": "CreateUserDto"}]`
- **Language marker:** `language = "csharp"` on all C# nodes

